<hr />
<dl style="margin-left: 2 em">
  <a name="chakra"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHAKRA (or CHAKKRA)</dt>
  <dd>A wheel-like emblem that represents the Buddhist Dharma Chakra (or wheel of 
  law) and which appears in a variety of different designs on the national flag 
  of India, the military flags of Thailand and several other flags both past and 
  present � an ashoka chakra (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb8.html#buddhistflag">Buddhist flag</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3680.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3680.gif" alt="[chakra]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3681.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3681.gif" alt="[chakra]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1441.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1441.gif" alt="[Dharma Chakra]" border="0" height="108"></a><br />
  <em>National Flag of <a href="in.html">India</a> and Detail (fotw); <a href="th_buddh.html">Buddhist Flag</a>, 
  Thailand (fotw)</em> </p>
  </dd>
  
  <hr/><a name="chalice"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHALICE</dt>
  <dd>A ceremonial cup usually in some precious metal, occasionally covered or shown with a communion wafer, 
  and used in most forms of Christian worship (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvch.html#christianflag">Christian flag 1)</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2532.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2532.gif" alt="[Chalice]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2076a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2076a.gif" alt="[Chalice]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4520.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4520.gif" alt="[Chalice]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br>
  <em>Flag of <a href="ch-gr164.html">Fanas</a>, Switzerland (fotw); Arms and 
  Flag of <a href="hr-pz-ja.html">Jak�i&#263;</a>, Croatia (fotw);
  </em></dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="chamferedswallowtail"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHAMFERED SWALLOW-TAIL</dt> 
  <dd>In UK usage a term that may be used to describe the shape, now obsolete, 
  of those guidons formerly carried by formations of cavalry � an angled 
  swallow-tail - see
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd1.html#descate">descate</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvg4.html#descate">guidon</a>&rsquo;.  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2158.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2158.gif" alt="angled pole" border="0" height="108" /></a><br>
  <em>Guidon of the </em> <a href="gb^glo2.html#rgyc"><em>Royal Gloucestershire Yeomanry 1797</em></a><em>, UK (fotw)
  </em>  <p>
  <em>Please note that these terms have been introduced by the Editors since no established alternatives could be found.</em>
  </dd>

  <hr/><a name="champagne"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHAMPAGNE</dt>
  <dd>An alternative heraldic term for base - &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb3.html#base">base 1)</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1163.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1163.gif" alt="[Champagne]" border="0" height="108" /></a></dd>

    
  <hr/><a name="chape"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHAP�</dt>
  <dd>The French heraldic term used when the divisions on a shield or banner of arms form a 
  triangle pointing upward, and employed by French heralds in place of the equivalent English 
  terms per chevron or per pile reversed &ndash; see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp3.html#perchevron">per chevron</a>&rsquo; and its following note, 
  plus the note 
  following &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp3.html#perpile">per pile</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp4.html#pile">pile 2)</a>&rsquo; 
  (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvch.html#chausse">chauss&#233;</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4697.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4697.gif" alt="[chap&eacute; example]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3683a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3683a.gif" alt="[chap&eacute; example]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3683.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3683.gif" alt="[chap&eacute; example]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br>
  <em>Flag of <a href="de-me-hh.html">Heiligenhaus</a>, Germany (fotw); 
  Arms and Flag of <a href="hr-kc.html">Koprivnica-Krizevci County</a>, Croatia 
  (fotw) </em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="chapelflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHAPEL FLAG </dt>
  <dd>In US army usage a flag, bearing a device corresponding to a particular religion, 
  displayed in a military chapel.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d073.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d073.gif" alt="[US Chapel Flag]" border="0" width="127" height="106"></a><br />
  <em>Christian Faith <a href="us^mcf.html">Chapel Flag</a>, US (fotw)</em> </p>
  </dd>
  <hr /><a name="chaplainflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHAPLAIN&#39;S FLAG </dt>
  <dd>In US army usage a flag, bearing a device corresponding to a particular religion, 
  flown in the field to designate the location of a chaplain's quarters or office, 
  or the site at which religious services are being held.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d075.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d075.gif" alt="[Jewish chaplain flag]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3697.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3697.gif" alt="[Muslim chaplain flag]" border="0" height="108"></a><br />
  <em><a href="us^mcf.html#chaplain">Jewish Faith</a> Chaplain�s Flag, US (fotw);
  <a href="us^mcf.html#mus">Muslim Faith</a> Chaplain�s Flag, US (fotw)</em> </p>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="chaplet"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHAPLET </dt>
  <dd>An alternative heraldic term for garland - see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-g.html#garland">garland 1)</a>&rsquo;. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d416.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d416.gif" alt="[chaplet]" border="0" height="108"></a><br />
  <em>Flag of </em> <a href="ch-ar010.html"><em>Sch&#246;nengrund</em></a><em>, 
  Switzerland (fotw)</em></dd>

  <hr /><a name="chapletofrue"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHAPLET OF RUE</dt>
  <dd>A term sometimes (inaccurately and incorrectly) used in place of crown of rue � see 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc9.html#crownofrue">crown of rue</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1356.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1356.gif" alt="[chaplet of rue]" border="0" height="108"></a><br />
  <em>Arms of <a href="de-sn.html#coa">Saxony</a>, Germany (fotw)</em>
  </dd>

  <hr /><a name="charbuncle"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHARBUNCLE</dt>
  <dd>An alternative heraldic term for escarbuncle - see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve4.html#escarbuncle">escarbuncle</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4698.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4698.gif" alt="[charbunkle]" border="0" height="108"></a><br />
  <em>Flag of <a href="de-rb-gn.html">Gnarrenburg</a>, Germany (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="charge"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHARGE </dt>
  <dd>1) Generically, any emblem, object or design placed upon the field of a flag 
  or shield (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt!dv-4.html">Appendix IV</a>&rsquo;). </dd>
  <dd>2) Specifically, a symbol placed upon the field of a flag, which is neither an emblem as 
  specifically defined herein, nor a badge (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-e.html#emblem">emblem</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-e.html#emblemst">emblem, state, national or royal</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-e.html#emblemmg">emblem military or governmental/departmental</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-b.html#badge">badge</a>&rsquo;). </dd>
  <dd>3) (v) The act of placing such a charge on a flag.
  <p><em>Please note however, that with a considerable degree 
  of heraldic justification, some sources propose the charge to be an integral part 
  of the design of a shield or banner of arms and usually not used separately, whereas, in general a badge 
  may. It is suggested therefore, that the entry &lsquo;</em><a href="vxt-dv-b.html#badge"><em>badge</em></a><em>
  (in heraldry)&rsquo;, and a suitable glossary or heraldic dictionary be consulted. 
  </em> </p>
  </dd>
  <hr /><a name="charged"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHARGED (or CHARGED WITH)</dt>
  <dd>1) In vexillology and heraldry the act of having placed a charge on a flag, shield or banner of 
  arms (especially &quot;charged with&quot;) 
  &ndash; to have defaced with a charge (see also &lsquo;<a href="#charge">charge</a>&rsquo; 
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-d.html#deface">deface</a>&rsquo;). 
  <br>
  2) In heraldry this term may also be used when one charge is placed upon (that is on top of) and within another � 
  but see �<a href="vxt-dvs9.html#surmountedby">surmounted by 2)</a>�
  (also �<a href="vxt-dv-d.html#debruised">debruised</a>�).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4227.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4227.gif" alt="[charged]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4228.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4228.gif" alt="[charged]" border="0" height="108"></a><br>
  <em>Flag of <a href="gb-e-ntt.html">Nottinghamshire</a>, UK (fotw); Arms of Altkirchen, Germany (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Altkirchen">Wikipedia</a>)</em>
  </dd>
    
  <hr/><a name="chausse"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHAUSS�</dt>
  <dd>The French heraldic term used when the divisions on a shield or banner of arms form a 
  triangle pointing downward, and employed by French heralds in place of the equivalent English 
  terms per chevron reversed or per pile &ndash; see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp3.html#perchevron">per chevron</a>&rsquo; and its following note, the note 
  following &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp3.html#perpile">per pile</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp4.html#pile">pile 2)</a>&rsquo;&nbsp; 
  (also �<a href="vxt-dvch.html#chape">chap&#233;</a>�).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4023.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4023.gif" alt="[chauss&eacute; example]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4023a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4023a.gif" alt="[chauss&eacute; example]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4024.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4024.gif" alt="[chauss&eacute; example]" border="0" height="108"></a><br>
  <em>Flag and Arms of <a href="fr-83.html#ban">Var</a>, France (fotw); Flag of
  <a href="pt-albav.html#vm">Valmajor</a>, Portugal (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr />
  <a name="checkeredflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHECKERED FLAG</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs5.html#sportsflag">sports flag 4)</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d588c.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d588c.gif" alt="[chequered flag]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br /><i><a href="xf@chex.html">Checkered flag </a>(fotw)</i>
  <dd>
  
  <hr />
  <a name="checky"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHECKY (CHECKERED, CHECKIE, CHEQUEY, CHEQUERED, CHEQUE, CHEQUES, CHEQUY or CHECQUY)</dt>
  <dd>1) In vexillology, the term used for a flag (or sometimes a charge) bearing more than four but 
  an otherwise varied number of rectangles (usually but not invariably squares) in alternating colours &ndash; 
  but see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc6.html#compony">compony</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvco.html#countercompony">counter-compony</a>&rsquo; 
  (also &lsquo;<a href="#charge">charge 1)</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-q.html#quarterly">quarterly</a>&rsquo;).</dd>
  <dd>2) In heraldry the alternative terms covering a shield or banner of arms, or an ordinary/charge thereon, bearing (not less than 
  twenty) squares of a metal and colour alternately. - but see  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve4.html#equipolle">equipoll&eacute;</a>&rsquo; and the note below, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc6.html#compony">compony</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvco.html#countercompony">counter-compony</a>&rsquo; (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvo2.html#ordinary">ordinary</a>&rsquo;). 

  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d077e.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d077e.gif" alt="flag of Croatia" border="0" height="108" /></a> 
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4278.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4278.gif" alt="[Example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d077.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d077.gif" alt="[Checky - North Brabant Netherlands]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br />
  <em>National 
  Flag of <a href="hr.html">Croatia</a>, Czechia (fotw); Flag of <a href="ba-10-ku.html">Kupres</a>, Bosnia and Herzegovina (fotw); Flag of <a href="nl-nb.html">North Brabant</a>, 
  Netherlands (fotw)&nbsp; </em>
  <p><em>Please note that in heraldry the exact number of squares (if more than twenty) is usually 
  left undefined, however, any number between ten and twenty squares is generally specified, and that in vexillology 
  the number of such rectangles (regardless of quantity) is often precisely regulated.</em></p>
  </dd>
  
  <hr/><a name="checkynine"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHECKY (or CHECKERED) OF NINE</dt>
  <dd>In heraldry see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve4.html#equipolle">equipoll&#233;</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2989.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2989.gif" alt="Checky of Nine" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Flag of <a href="pt-vlcmc.html">Macieira de Cambra</a>, Portugal (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr/><a name="chessboard"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHESSBOARD</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="#checky">checky</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1473.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1473.gif" alt="Ostrorog, Poland " border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
