  </dd>
  
  <hr/><a name="chevaltrap"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHEVAL-TRAP</dt>
  <dd>An alternative heraldic term to caltrap - see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-c.html#caltrap">caltrap</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1414.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1414.gif" alt="caltrap" border="0" height="108" /></a></dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="chevron"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHEVRON </dt>
  <dd>1) On flags any &lsquo;V&rsquo; shaped charge on a flag irrespective of the width of the 
  arms.  The standard orientation of a chevron on flags is the same as 2) below so 
  when the apex is towards the top of the flag it is a standard or simple chevron, 
  when towards the base of the flag a reversed on inverted chevron, however, when 
  the apex is towards the fly it may be called a hoist chevron, and with the apex 
  towards the hoist a fly chevron (see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvi6.html#inverted">inverted</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr2.html#reversed">reversed</a>&rsquo;).</dd>
  <dd>2) In heraldry, the term for a charge with arms in the shape of a generally (but not invariably) 
  inverted letter &lsquo;V&rsquo;, and heraldic use frequently suggests that a chevron should have a width equal 
  to one-fifth the field of a banner of arms or shield � but see the second following note 
  (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp1.html#party">party</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp3.html#perchevron">per chevron</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-n.html#naissant">naissant</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp4.html#pile">pile 2)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr2.html#reversed">reversed 2)</a>&rsquo;). 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4279.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4279.gif" alt="chevron" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4576.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4576.gif" alt="chevron" border="0" width="108" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d827b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d827b.gif" alt="chevron" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br />
  <em>Flag of <a href="be-vovhb.html">Horebeke</a>, Belgium (fotw); 
  Flag of the <a href="vex-bhvs.html">Bulgarian Vexillological Society</a> (fotw);
  Flag of <a href="nl-fr_bl.html">Boelenslaan</a>, Netherlands (fotw)</em><p><em>Notes<br>a) With regard to 1), the Editors have adopted a heraldic 
  model in defining a chevron on flags, however, please note also that there are 
  conflicting definitions with regard to the standard vexillological orientation of 
  a chevron and that usage of this term has not yet settled upon a consistent approach.<br>
  b) With regard to 2), a chevron may also be embowed, wavy, embattled or otherwise differenced � see - 
  see &lsquo;</em><a href="vxt-dv-e.html#embattled"><em>embattled</em></a><em>&rsquo; 
  &lsquo;</em><a href="vxt-dv-e.html#embowed"><em>embowed</em></a><em>&rsquo; and
  &lsquo;</em><a href="vxt-dv-w.html#wavy"><em>wavy</em></a><em>&rsquo;.</em></p>
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d827e.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d827e.gif" alt="Lamboing, Switzerland" border="0" width="105" height="105" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d428a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d428a.gif" alt="De Valom, Netherlands" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d428b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d428b.gif" alt="De Valom, Netherlands" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Flag of </em> <a href="ch-be210.html"><em>Lamboing</em></a><em>, Switzerland (fotw); 
  Arms and Flag of </em> <a href="nl-fr_dv.html"><em>De Valom</em></a><em>, The 
  Netherlands (fotw)</em> </dd>
  <hr /><a name="chevronel"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHEVRONEL</dt>
  <dd>A heraldic term used when two or more chevrons are displayed together on a shield or banner of arms, and heraldic use frequently 
  suggests that a chevronel should be one-half the width of a chevron (see &lsquo;<a href="#chevron">chevron</a>&rsquo; above). 
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d4699a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4699a.gif" alt="[chevronel]" border="0" height="108" /></a> 
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4699.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4699.gif" alt="[chevronel]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Arms and Flag of <a href="pt-tnvzb.html">Zibreira</a>, Portugal (fotw)</em><p>
    <em>Please note that in heraldry the standard orientation of a chevronel is the same as that of a chevron and that 
  variations of this standard may be described using the terminology given in 2)&rsquo; above.</em>
  </dd>
    
  <hr /><a name="chief"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHIEF </dt>
  <dd>A heraldic term for the top horizontal section of a shield or banner of arms, 
  however, heraldic use frequently suggests that a chief should be one-third of 
  the total depth of that shield, of a banner of arms or any quartering thereof (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-b.html#bannerofarms">banner of arms</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb3.html#base">base</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf1.html#fillet">fillet 2)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs3.html#shield">shield 2)</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2991.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2991.gif" alt="[Prince Edward Island]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d578.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d578.gif" alt="[chief example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2990.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2990.gif" alt="[Ra&#295;al &#288;did]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br><em>Flag of 
  <a href="mt-45.html">Ra&#295;al &#288;did</a>, Malta (fotw); Example; Flag of <a href="ca-pe.html">Prince Edward Island</a>, Canada (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="christsknightscross"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHRIST&rsquo;S KNIGHT&rsquo;S CROSS</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcs.html#knightsofchrist">cross of the order of the knights of Christ</a>&rsquo;.
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d1873.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1873.gif" alt="Order of the Knights of Christ" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Putative Banner of the <a href="pt_oxp.html">Order of the Knights of Christ</a> (fotw)</em>
  </dd>

  
  <hr /><a name="christianflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHRISTIAN FLAG </dt>
  <dd>1) Generically one of a number of designs symbolizing Christianity &ndash; an ecclesiastic, ecclesiastical or church flag - but see  
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr1.html#religiousflag">religious flag</a>&rsquo; (also 
  &lsquo;<a href="#churchflag">church flag 2)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm1.html#marianflag">marion flag</a>&rsquo;).</dd>
  <dd> 2) Specifically in largely US usage, the white flag with a blue canton containing a red Latin cross designed in 1897 by Charles Overton, and used by various Protestant groups 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1682.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1682.gif" alt="Armenian Catholic Church" border="0" height="108" /></a>  
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d525.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d525.gif" alt="Anglican Church" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d081.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d081.gif" alt="[Christian flag]" border="0" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br />
  <em>Flag of <a href="rel-am.html">Armenian Catholics</a> (fotw); The <a href="rel-acc.html">Anglican Catholic Church</a>, US (fotw); 
  <a href="rel-chr.html">Charles Overton&rsquo;s Flag</a> (fotw)</em>
  <p><em>Please note with regard to 2) that usage of the Charles Overton flag was 
  originally (largely) confined to the United States, but evidence of growing use elsewhere 
  has been reported.</em></p>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="christiiferus"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHRISTIFERUS </dt>
  <dd>A medieval term, now obsolete, for the bearer of a standard, flag or banner 
  upon which the figure of Christ crucified was depicted. </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="churchbanner"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHURCH BANNER</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvba.html#banner">banner 3)</a>&rsquo; (also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-l.html#labarum">labarum 2)</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2072.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2072.gif" alt="[church banner]" border="0" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br>
  <a href="http://artfromthesoul.com">artfromthesoul.com</a> 
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="churchclasp"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHURCH CLASP</dt>
  <dd>A direct translation of the German term <em>kirchenspange </em>� but see �<a href="vxt-dvf6.html#forkedcross">forked cross</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3397.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3397.gif" alt="[church clasp]" border="0" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br><em>Arms of <a href="https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bezirk_Affoltern">Affoltern</a>, 
  Switzerland (Wikipedia)</em> 
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="churchflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHURCH FLAG </dt>
  <dd>1) See &lsquo;<a href="#christianflag">Christian flag 1)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr1.html#religiousflag">religious flag</a>&rsquo;.</dd>
  <dd>2) In UK usage and some others, the flag flown from or outside a church; 
  particularly that flown from an Established (or Anglican) Church defaced with 
  the appropriate diocesan arms.</dd>
  <dd>3) A direct translation of the German term <em>kirckenfahne</em> � but see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-l.html#labarum">labarum 2)</a>&rsquo;.  

  <p style="height: 131px">
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2281.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2281.gif" alt="[church flag example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d579a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d579a.gif" alt="[church flag example]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em><a href="rel-epis.html">Episcopal Churches</a>, US (fotw); The 
  <a href="gb_ce-di.html#canterbury">Anglican Diocese of Canterbury</a> (fotw)</em></dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="churchpennant"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">CHURCH PENNANT (or PENDANT) </dt>
  <dd>In US, UK and some other naval usage, the pennant hoisted aboard a warship 
  or naval shore establishment during religious services (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb5.html#bethelflag">bethel flag</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf5.html#flyingangelflag">flying angel flag</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d083.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d083.gif" alt="[Church pennant - UK, Netherlands]" border="0" width="343" height="106" /></a>&nbsp;
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3486.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3486.gif" alt="[Church pennant - Portugal]" border="0" height="108" /></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;
  <br />
  <em>Pennants: <a href="gb-chpen.html">UK</a>/<a href="nl-chpnt.html">The Netherlands</a> 
  and <a href="pt~n.html#chp">Portugal</a> (fotw)</em><p><em>Please note however, that in US usage this may also be called 
  a worship pennant, particularly when in connection with a non-Christian service.</em></p>
  <p>
    <a href="../images/v/vxt-d083b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d083b.gif" alt="[Church pennant - Jewish worship pennant US]" border="0" width="325" height="106" />
  </a><br />
    <em><a href="us^nchrh.html#jwp">Jewish Worship Pennant</a>, US (fotw) </em>
